76561198031820408,Recommended,239840,15910678,"Posted: 19 May, 2015",all,RK Skuller,"Great game !!!!! This game is about the only thing I found to a zombie, survival, base builder/Manager sim out there.This game has the social tough choices similar to "" State of decay "" with a more important role in balancing upgrading your base with providing man power towards improving morale.*********Things You should know*********Combat in the game is turn based exploring and out of combat moving is not-The combat system in this game allows you to do many of the things you would do if lets say zombies were real. For example:You enter a block with a large Super Store, the path to the uber-lootable building is blocked by numerous zombies and obstacles that could hide even more zombies but luckily you had adopted an intelligent german shepard police dog. So you get the dog to lure the zombies in front of the building down an alley to the side of the building then returns once it lost the horde. now to enter the building, you decide to best leave your dog in front of the building to guard/alert you should the horde come back. The store is loaded with supplies that you so very much need. You round a corner and get pounced on by a zombie luckily your other compadrae was right behind you and sledge hammers the zombie in the back of the head before you became a torn open meat bag. Now you carry on with looting the building and come to an office door you open the door, axe in hand ready to fight a possible zombie only to find a looter aiming a gun right at you.He fires shooting right past your head. you duck back away from the room where the crazed gun man resides. Seconds later you hear pounding on an emergency exit where your pooch had lost the horde on the back alley of the building. They heard the gun shot. You and your partner high tale it out of there as the door busts in from the weight of the horde. The looter is now trapped in the room struggling to stay alive. You are half way out of the building as you hear moans and gunfire in your wake. You meet up with your loyal pup and flee the store now once again claimed by the dead.-That is the sort of game play I love about Dead State I give it  5 out of 5"
76561198056019702,Recommended,239840,33487562,Posted: 12 July,all,ephemeraltoast,"I loved enough about this game to play it all the way to the end, but it has some major flaws and it's not for everyone. It has a lot of heart, but like the zombies you fight in it, it's missing some brains.Easily the best thing about the game is the writing. You will meet 40-50 strongly drawn individuals in a full playthrough and, as the leader of your shelter, you will need to manage their concerns, demands, and occasional breakdowns via individual interactions and through more collective decision-making known as ""crisis events."" This is great stuff. You'll constantly feel the tension of having to manage so many conflicting personalities in order to keep everyone safe, fed, and what now passes for comfortable. Resource management is also a critical part of the game--at least in the beginning. Assigning people to various tasks in the shelter to best use their skills and your scarce resources is an engaging challenge, compounded by the fact that many of your shelter inhabitants have strong preferences about how much danger they or someone they love should be in. Base management and personality management are very strongly merged and if you like that sort of thing, you'll love this part of the game.Unfortunately, the other major part of the game--scavanging and combat--is much less strong. First of all, ignore any comparisons to X-Com you might see in the promo materials. Combat here is nothing like X-Com; there isn't even a cover mechanic. If you are looking for a deep tactical experience, you will not find it here. It's frustrating because there is a lot of wasted potential. For instance, there is a ""noise"" mechanic in which using louder (and more powerful) weapons, like guns, will draw more zombies to your location. In the early game, this is very dangerous, but you can also use it to your advantage by luring zombies to attack human foes. You feel pretty badass the first time you manage to pull it off! Unfortunately, zombies pretty quickly become unthreatening once you find any decent armor, and they never ""evolve"" or become any more dangerous. Yet you will be fighting those same zombies throughout the entire game.This problem is compounded by the fact that every zombie on the map takes its turn at the SAME TIME, regardless of whether you have aggroed it or not. So aggroing even ONE zombie, when the typical map can have 30-50 of them, means sitting there for 10-20 seconds while the game processes the turn of every zombie on the map who is not doing anything but standing around picking its nose. It turns what should be an incredibly brief and decisive battle against a completely unthreatening single foe into an agonizing waiting game. And the game lags horribly while this is happening. It is excruciating, and you may find yourself intentionally aggroing every zombie on the map by being as loud as possible just to get it over with. So what should have been an interesting combat mechanic soon becomes merely a tool to bypass the irritations of the game engine.It's also worth noting that if you scavenge every day (and there is no reaosn not to), the nail-biting scarcity of the early game quickly passes and by mid-game you will find yourself swimming in food and supplies, even if you take in literally every survivor that you find, as I did. I thought that playing this way would force me to make harder and harder decisions about how to keep this ever-growing number of people safe and fed, when in fact having more people in the shelter makes the game easier, as you will more quickly be able to complete upgrades that produce more food and parts for you. Soon enough, I actually ran out of useful things for survivors to do around the shelter, and most of them spent their days enjoying the seemingly endless bourbon and bon-bons I was scavenging up for them.And for whatever it's worth: at least one major and obvious ending was scrapped from the game, and the one I got was lackluster, to say the least.So that's Dead State. It has a lot to recommend it, but a lot of problems too. If I could give it a sideways thumb, I would--but since I was willing to put up with its flaws because I really enjoyed the good parts, maybe some other people will feel that way too. If you want an open world with strong characters, interesting decision-making, and base management that is engaging for at least half of the game, give it a shot. If you hate reading and want deep tactical combat and a game engine that doesn't feel like it's held together with string and tape, give this one a miss."
