,Recommended,239840,26615846,"Posted: 15 November, 2016",all,[UPV] Zenpei,"I followed this game with great anticipation for a good chunk of time. After I had read about it in a Gaming magazine back in mid 2010 I was thrilled to hear about a Zombie game with base management elements. I have not been disappointed.The gameplay is absolutly for the more hardcore zombie fans as it's clunky animations and turn-based combat system allows for some criticism. However it's good. It is worth 20€ for what it is.The graphics are not to be amazed over but the quality of the smoothness when it runs is worth some degree. I have seen games with worse graphics that ran like a stick in the mud.That said I love the attention to detail. If you are low on food and get a really good haul of it you will see in your pantry the massive amounts of food displayed. There will be close to nothing if you have close to no food. However have your stocks full and the pantry looks like a fully stocked super-market.DoubleBear productions are worthy of some praise as the game kept me going. I have replayed the early-mid part of the game several times and I'm pleased. The options to craft your own backstory in the beginning is somewhat good but the dialouge options could feel heavy at times.The cutscenes are nothing new or impressive as they just teleprot characters to an area to have them setup for dialouge. However the written story gives each and every NPC character. I was sure some NPC would be a minor leader but was not and some reactions of other NPCs were great. I personally loved tormenting the poor priest when he crossed my decision at one point by forcing him to do something he did not want to. That is great for immersion and for roleplaying.However the sound is very simple but it works for the setting, it won't go down like a piece of art. However it works none the less.The only true complaint I have is the RNG as it can sometimes ♥♥♥♥ you over and the AI system. So first things first. The construction and resource system. I do not like that certain upgrades feel so ""limited"" such as the garden part. I can easily imagine more outdoor areas get turned into growing areas. So there could be an update for that. The resources gained can vary very heavily sometimes and that can lead to weird situations when the need to upgrade is high. I have had the unlucky time of never being able to get the highest upgrade for the wall in one of my many playthroughs. The RNG does however what an RNG should.The AI system can be very frustrating at times. I can setup a trap for raiders to stumble into a herd of zombies only to ahve the dead attack me instead. Same goes for raiders being so extremly dumb as they make continoues fire of thier firearms to attract over 100 zombies to the map. That♥♥♥♥♥♥is dangerous. They should know that and they should use firearms as a last resort. But the system does not allow it.Overall, I love this game. It's one of the few good games that truly explores what an zombie apocalypse would be about. Yes there are zombies. But people are the biggest danger."
76561198036943999,Not Recommended,239840,35258092,Posted: 28 September,all,SamuraiJones,"This game really does an excellent job of capturing the adventure of leading a ragtag group of zombie apocolypse survivors. Unfortunately, it also captures the tedium of a managing the established settlement that those survivors eventually evolve into.This game is a zombie survivor base-building game. It's got all the features. Resource management, job assignments, base building, structural upgrades and repairs. It's got character levelling and growth options, personal needs and beliefs, both base moral and individual moods, as well as scripted but belivable character interactions. There's even some reasonably sophisticated politics that reacts to situations. Random events, situations with multiple options. Base defense, exploration, scavanging, fighting zombies as well as various human groups (each with their own unique equipment and personality). Plenty of features, the majority of them done quite well.That said, there are many aspects of the game that are just frustrating. Base management is a pain. You control a character and he/she can only control aspects of the base from certain locations. So there's alot of running back and forth between rooms to tweak the aspects of the base. Alot of scanning the halls, looking for the one character so you can deliver your quest item. You can't access character screens unless they're in your party and outside the base, and you can only access inventory screens from a single place in the base. Items can get lost in players inventories, forcing you to regularly go through characters inventories one at a time, to see if they're carrying anything important.The missons suffers from a major problem, in that it has realtime sneak/explore/loot mode and a turn-based fighting mode, and transitions are handled very poorly. The instigator of combat gets initiative, which makes it a huge tactical advantage to be able to control position, timing and agro as combat starts. Unfortunately, the transition to and from turn-base isn't handled well, so most of the challenge is learning to navigate the transitions.An example I struggled with many times at first: you'll be sneaking up behind a zombie, then you trigger turn based combat and move your first character a a little closer... but you didn't get close enough for him to see you. There's no agroed zombies, so combat automatically ends. The game returns to realtime and immediately the team regroups with the first member, alerting the zombie to their presence as they do so. Now combat restarts with your whole team in different positions, and since the zombie ""started combat"" he gets initiative like you're being ambushed. Now he turns and takes a big bite out of that first survivor, possibly infecting him, and now you may have to spend the rest of the game (maybe 40 hours?) making sure he's got a steady supply of medicine so he doesn't turn.A different kind of frustrating... the combat is slow. On a big map, you might sneak up and attack one zombie, but the combat system has to process the 50 other zombies all over the map (who are just standing around cuz they're across the map and haven't agroed yet). It's like we're playing a 1998 strategy game... the PC's turns tend to be five times as long as yours when nothing is happening. And if there are enemy survivors are fighting zombies somewhere across the map... then you have to wait for all the animations even though you can't see them. Tactically it's a win, but it takes soooooo long.Camera angles are bad too. You can spin the camera but not adjust the angle, and walls are high and ceilings don't always disappear when you want them to. I had one battle where we fought under a gas-station canopy where the canopy wouldn't disappear, so I just had to keep spinning the cameara, trying to get a glimpse of what was happening underneath. Thin halls and cramped rooms are difficult as well.Last gripe: Late in the game, zombies become trival enemies, but their bites can infect survivors, which is an incurable catastrophy. But if you've gotten to this point, you know how to be careful. It's not hard, it's just slow and tedious. Going through a suburb, stealth killing one zombie at a time for routine scavenging operations is mind-numbingly boring, but such a big part of the game.Anyway, all that said, pretty much everything I haven't complained about is very good. Challenging combat is fun. You need to pick your battles, as different groups have different tiers of equipment. I'll never forget the first time my squad bumped into a pair of Coyote gangsters. It's still terrifying bumping into military defectors squads with my zombie-equipped scavanging team. Monitoring your food and medicine levels is always a little tense, and it's a rush of relief when you find that rare stash of supplies. You love dumpsters, hoping for rotten fruit and scrap wood. Finding a AK47 is not nearly as satisfying as a 10lbs bag of beans (Or that time I found the twinky factory and carried back 120lbs of twinkies and raw sugar. Not sure if they'd worship me or crucify me).I'm much more patient than most gamers, but this one was too much for me. If you want to finish this game, it will take an extremely patient person (or at least someone who is committed to finishing it, regardless of whether they enjoy it). On the other hand, some people probably play the start, but set it down when it becomes a sea of routine scavanging. If you think you're one of those two types of people, maybe this game is for you, but it was just too slow for me."
76561197975744062,Not Recommended,239840,34167654,Posted: 11 August,all,stuguy909,"It pains me to say that I cannot recommend this game to friends.  I absolutely enjoyed my time in development, but always wanted more.  More story, more locations, more things to build / do, etc.  However, the game ended development, and suddenly, support stopped.  This review comes years after the game as since ended all support and development.  This review will explain the game as is, long after it ended abruptly as the game's ending is.Dead State allows your to create a character in made up middle of nowhere town, Texas, do a quick air plane crash tutorial, then find yourself leading a group of survvors in a school.  There is an interesting dynamic trying to play sides, or just not giving a crap, ultimately, doing what's necessary for the group and your ability to lead.  You get a team of characters, and there is some story, and it's nice.  I spent a great deal of time weighing options, exploring, and scavenging the map for supplies.  The turnbased combat is fun, so I will not dock the review points in that area.  However, after about 10 hours or so, the game loses all story elements and becomes a grind to the finish.  What I mean by grind is, sleeping until the end because game balancing and actually finishing the story through the designated timeline never happened.After you have a decent amount of supplies and upgrade your school fort to max, there really isn't much point to doing anything.  I can send out my super SWAT team and roll through just about any challenge, boss fights included.  A little preparation and know how makes the static maps rather easy to beat on all difficulties.  So, after skipping through the last 20 days or so, the game ended just about as fast as it began.  It felt rushed, and a let down.  Having backed the game from the beginning, played the beta, then the final, I can tell you that it's a fun game, for a short time, but then ends abruptly, or just gets boring, and there's no point.There is almost zero replayability.  No bonus rounds or alternate stories.  You know what happens, and can google how to get the best endings.  Total waste of time.  For a zombie sim, it seemed promising.  During development, I loved the take on turn based zombie tactics.  However, considering Project Zomboid is still being supported, and is older than this title...the developer should be shunned for not finishing what he started."
