76561198030374042,Recommended,239840,14481994,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,commander515,"Dead State is a survival/horror RPG with strong base-building elements set in the zombie apocalypse. (Think Fallout Tactics but open-ended with a strategic/resource management layer). As the elected leader of a small group of survivors, you must go on runs for supplies, locate and rescue other survivors, allocate resources and gradually build up your shelter from a bare-bones school into a fortified complex. You must constantly deal with not only the hordes of walking dead, but perhaps more importantly, the living, who in many cases are even more dangerous.Everyone you find has their own story, their own motivations, priorities, and attitude towards life and what is happening out in the world. As your shelter and group grows in size and reputation, people will eventually begin coming to you, leaving you with a choice as to how to deal with them. Letting in everyone may seem like a good idea, but eventually you will have to deal with the personality conflicts that arise between certain members of your group. Threats to your survival will arise both from the outside and from inside the shelter itself, forcing you to make tough, black-or-white decisions about how to deal with them. Food shortages, supply shortages, morale problems, and epidemics of disease are daily specters. Do a bad job in dealing with these issues, and other strong-willed members of the group may decide to challenge your leadership, putting you at risk of being thrown out of your own shelter.Combat is squad-based, turn-based, and tactical. Traveling to any of the game's many scattered locations to scavenge for supplies invariably results in hostile encounters with the both walking dead and rival groups of hostile scavengers or survivors. Each member of your group has a specific set of skills that may make them suitable as a melee fighter, ranged combatant, or combat medic, and it is up to you to equip and assemble your squad with those things in mind, using whatever weapons, armor, equipment and medical supplies you have managed to scrounge or manufacture. The pros and cons of various weapons and armor, the layout of external obstacles and the internals of buildings, and proper noise management all play into getting your scavenging team in and out of dangerous situations alive and, hopefully, with backpacks full of badly-needed loot.The game does have some interface and gameplay issues, and there have been alot of reports from users about crashes as well as glitches and bugs ranging from annoying to game-breaking throughout the game's release history. Personally, at 60 hours/50 game days in, I have not encountered anything more than a few minor glitches that, while annoying, have not seriously impacted my gameplay, in addition to a few isolated crashes. Luckily, the devs wisely included an automated bug-reporting tool with the full game that will allow you to notify them whenever there is a crash. I would advise anyone who buys the game to backup your save files just in case something catastrophic happens. I will admit that the game could use a few more updates, in my opinion, but more in terms of things to be added or modified rather than fixed outright. Overall I feel that the basic mechanics of the game are solid, providing a compelling and realistic simulation of trying to lead a group of survivors through the zombie apocalypse. I definitely recommend it to anyone who enjoys open-ended RPGs or turn-based strategy games."
76561198109612756,Recommended,239840,12421593,"Posted: 9 October, 2014",all,veryinky,"Early Access Review:Single Player, Turn based, isometric, dialog heavy RPG, with resource management, a world map with near a hundred tactical locations on it and a central hub/base which can be upgraded.Plays a lot like if Fallout 1/2 & Jagged Alliance 1/2 gameplay were mixed with Walking Dead's story. Also reminded me of State of Decay, but with turn based combat instead of 3rd person realtime, in that it focuses heavily on upgrading a shelter, scavenging and dealing with NPC allies along with external threats. Dead State is centered around the ""Shelter"", a school that the player's allies have fortified, The problems the player has to solve are both internal and external, NPCs have problems with each other, shelter upgrades break down or NPCs want to know what happened to their loved ones or people they knew. Then there's external threats in the form of hostile factions that the player can negotiate with, antagonize or even wipe out.  So far I've encountered 35 recruitable NPCs who have their own story to tell if I ask them, or sometimes don't ask them. Every morning in the game there's invariably one or two people at my room's door wanting me to either deal with a problem or to provide me with a new location on the world map to explore.One of the central game mechancis though is Crisis Events, which deal with large problems that the entire shelter's population wants solved in one way or the other. Diplomacy by the player can help persuade NPCs that the player's decision is the correct one. Or the player can choose an option that pleases the most people to increase the mood (personal) and morale(entire population) of the Shelter.I also like how easy it is to mod the dialogs in this game. So I can fix problems or change things that I don't like which is always a plus.I recommend this game for anyone who's a fan of old school RPGs."
