,Recommended,239840,34960524,Posted: 14 September,all,Silhouette,"Dead State takes on a game setting that has been done before: A zombie apocalypse has occurred, and you're tasked with surviving by scrounging up whatever materials and rescuing and recruiting any survivors you can find. While it is a tried-and-sometimes-true genre, I feel like Dead State does manage to make it interesting, at least. The beginning is possibly it's strongest point, when you're tasked with fortifying a high-school that ends up becoming your base of operations.With a handful of other survivors, each with their own personalities, quirks, strengths and weaknesses in different aspects of contribution, you're supposed to somehow ration supplies, assign objectives, get crew assigned to different items, and find a way to go out a scavenge without becoming a citizen of the new apocalypse. It honestly becomes an interesting take on group management in a strenuous situation, and the experience is punctuated with semi-schedules events that take place throughout the game depending on the survivors present and the situation you're in, even sometimes requiring you to make difficult decision that impact the game in a drastic way.The other portion of the game pertains to the scavenging, and makes up a sizable portion of the game and is arguably the most frequent portion you'll work with outside of the former. Scavenging sees you moving about on a large map and trying to uncover locations of interest, while also trying to manage inventory and supplies during the journey. Once you uncover a location, you're usually able to enter the area's local map and move about, most often encountering zombies, looters, hostile survivors and friendly units that you can potentially recruit and bring about to your cause. Usually, the latter are the more interesting of these, as they often come with encounters unique to them and often showcase the developer's talents in context clues and storytelling.Combat takes place in a grid-based movement system where all units take turns and have various actions based on their equipment, and on an AP system which limits the amount of actions a single character can perform in a round. It's nothing too drastically new, so I won't go terribly into detail. It has had some known bugs, however, such as looters being killed by zombies, and taking a rather large number of rounds to turn, before you can kill the now zombified-looter and end combat.PROS:-Excellent marriage of Group Management and Zombie genres, with some exploration and turn-based grid-aligned combat, to boot.-While the game largely follows a set path in terms of major events, it does offer quite a large number of optional, semi-random events that can drastically impact the way the game progresses. Not necessarily to the point of providing several greatly different endings, but it can definitely change the game in a good way.-A truly great instance of developers with a penchant for character writing. Not every character drips with rainbows of uniqueness, but the situations are interesting and presented in ways that seem believable, which lends a great amount of atmosphere and interest to the cast, where they'd normally suffer from having too many on board.-Context is done masterfully in this game, as most times you can explore a location and see a story unfolding in front of you without a single written word or moving picture. This is usually most impressive when you're rescuing survivors, as you can often piece together terrible, tragic, or even sometimes horrifying stories simply by looking around the area first.CONS:-Unfortunately, as time goes on, the strong start does fade somewhat, and the game can sometimes seem more like menial tasking when you're waiting for the next day to arrive, and the end can seem like it is taking forever to arrive.-A somewhat weak ending, although there are some slight variations depending on your decisions or the events you took part in.-Some events are almost down-right secrets, as they can be almost entirely too easy to miss without knowledge beforehand.Even so, I'd recommend trying Dead State, at the very least. It's an underrated gem that really does deserve more coverage than it gets, and if you're into these genres, you really can't go wrong."
