76561197993118789,Recommended,239840,29250727,Posted: 14 January,all,nerloch,"In the game of attrition, there are no winnersAt the moment of writing this review, The Steam page for Dead State Reanimated rates this game as mostly positive and that is how I would rate my experience playing it: For every great thing this game does, it is usually followed by a major flaw that undermines the Dead State’s overall impression. If you like to play modern RPGs like Mass Effect, The Witcher 3 or Dragon Age, chances are you won’t find this game enjoyable. But if you fondly remember old RPG classics, like Fallout 1 and 2, or Baldur’s Gate series, and you’re armed with patience then you will enjoy Dead State… most of the time. Allow me to dissect this game for you (no pun intended):Pros:+ Good overall writing and gameplay+ Tactical and satisfying turn-based combat+ Interesting noise level, survival and experience system+ Decent sim management gameplay while in the shelter, with various resources that need to be balanced+ Lots of diverse and unique allies that will join your cause, each with different personality, wants and demands+ Strong level design and good, albeit simplistic artistic and graphical presentationCons:- Game has a very sluggish pace with unavoidable grinding- Quests are far and few, mostly fetch-based and primitive- Disappointing end game content- Thrown weapons are unbalanced- Combat rounds can drag on and game is plentiful with annoying bugs- Limited lore and zombie tropes make the game world a very uninteresting place to reside in- UI and inventory are needlessly complex and counter-intuitive- Minimalistic sound and music design serve to the detriment of game’s atmosphereDead State was made by many creative individuals, including Brian Mitsoda who was a writer for the legendary game Vampire the Masquerade Bloodlines, and that means the writing in this game is constantly on a high level of polish. All dialogues in Dead State are well written, as well are many data items you’ll find as you explore the world, which carry poignant and memorable articles to read. Nearly 50 allies you’ll have a chance to meet are all well-rounded characters that will follow you on your adventures or help you build more things in the shelter, if you are on their good side. But the off trade is that they don’t evolve as in other games with fewer companions that are extremely well-written and change dramatically as the game goes on.You are stuck in a world overrun by zombies, and you’ll need people, resources and the main headquarter to survive. The Shelter you find at the start of the game is an interesting concept, as it can be upgraded in order to provide a bonus to protection or a new type or resource against the overwhelming odds. There are many resources in the game you’ll have collect if you want to survive another day: food, fuel, spare parts and luxury items all grant mood boosts to you and allies, and keeping them well feed and taken care of is very important, otherwise they’ll fall into depression, inner-struggle and violence or will abandon you completely. That is why you’ll have to collect as much resources on your travels as you can.While you travel on the map, you’ll encounter many settlements that may be peaceful, but usually want you dead. All levels in the game you visit are well designed with many small and welcoming details developers could have easily omit, and add a lot to the overall atmosphere of the game. You’ll have to watch on the amount of noise you make, measured in decibels, otherwise you’ll attract the restless undead to your current location. You can also use the noise to you benefit, by directing zombies to the dangerous living enemies, while you wait out their clash to end and scavenge the remains of the battle. The living are the most daunting enemies in the game, as most of them liberally use firearms that can easily incapacitate you and your allies, and make a lot of unnecessary noise. Zombies on the other hand serve as an obstacle and a nuisance, since they are slow and their attacks are limited. However they can infect you if you are not careful, slowly leading to your doom.Leveling system in Dead State also differs from other RPGs: you only gain experience by surviving another day, and securing as much resources as you can. Surviving battle encounters yield you no experience, but you do get from it various traditional weapons and firearms that can be upgraded in the shelter to be more precise and deadly.  The combat is similar to first two Fallout games, where your positioning, use of a correct weapon on a correct enemy, and wisely using your skills and setting traps and snares are key to your victory. The longer the combat prolongs, chances of your survival diminish significantly. But there is a negative side to this type of combat: turns can slow down as more and more enemies enter the fray, human enemies can go dumb occasionally and move around not knowing how to get to you. Thrown weapons such as grenades break the careful balance of all weapons in the game as they can be flung so far, that if they are aimed at you, you’ll have no option from protecting yourself from their devastating effects.Biggest flaw of Dead State is the slow pace the game is developing and the main story is resolving. There are no traditional quests, with self-contained stories to tell and dramatic impact, only simple list of things to do for you or for your allies. And almost all of them involve annoying fetch-me–this and fetch-me-that demands. The number of encounters on the global map is limited and when you discover them all, you’ll have nothing to do but to wait for the end of the game to begin. And the amount of grinding you have to do is staggeringly bad: everything that is not nailed to the ground, you’ll have to pick up at some point. Your and allies’ Inventory will fill up so quickly that you’ll be forced to go back to the shelter to unload everything you’ve found and then return again to the latest destination to haul the rest of the stuff. This kind of pick-up-deliver-pick-up-again philosophy drags the entire pace of the game down and your enjoyment as well. You’ll also struggle with bafflingly illogical interface: how to split objects in your inventory and move them around, how to access the inventory of the vehicle, how to access skills you can use in combat and how many steps you have to take to assign your allies daily chores to do. And if that doesn’t drive you crazy, a letdown of the end content, the final battle and abrupt endings will leave you wanting for more grandiose conclusion. Music is un-intrusive and forgettable, while sound effects are minimal and underused, thus missing the chance for them to aid in building more memorable atmosphere and emphasize the dialogues and emotional bonds you and your allies share.Still, for me Dead State manages to be an overall mostly positive experience. I wish this kind of game wasn’t settled among zombies, for me one of the most overused and least interesting/frightening horror tropes and it is too bad that the game didn’t try to change and evolve our expectations regarding zombies. But at one point in the game, pressured by many choices, good and bad that I’ve made, and combat encounters I’ve survived and will have to endure, I started to adopt the ruthless survivalist way of thinking without even noticing at first. As I always want to play and do play as a good guy, this game made me aware of how enjoyable it can be to be a bad guy once in a while :D Thus I give it a cautious recommendation to the fans of classic RPG games and zombies, but I’ll also understand anyone who finds the amount of flaws to be a bit too much."
76561198006690286,Recommended,239840,17564915,"Posted: 16 August, 2015",all,suurimonster,"I only played Reanimated, following my usual rules of giving games at least 6 months after release to solve the main problems. I finished the game, fairly completely, maybe missing 2 or 3 characters due to time, and I also saw two of the possible, positive endings. As an experience, one of the best games I've played in a long time, coming close to the original JA2 experience and surpassing it in certain places. Played on highest difficulty levels, but not iron man (I have a job and a family...;-))Pros:For this gaming genre, a very refeshing theme.Early game captures the survival aspects well, with shortages of people, food and equipment.Interactions between characters are quite deep, with serious and not obvious consequences to your actions. The game is not afraid of serious issues and does not give easy answers.Zombies behave like zombies in combat...be careful and quiet, and they are easy kills.Writing is very good - I especially enjoyed the final discussions after one of the endings, and the little touches from the characters.Combat is fun, and you feel a strong progression in skill as your stats and weapons improve. Humans are a significant challenge early game, with military almost overwhelming, but only difficult in large numbers at the end.Lots of easter eggs! The RPG codex was a highlight...Cons:The base building aspect is over by about halfway through the game. I would like to see many more options here, as even the weapon options are not that interesting.I am not sure if I missed something, but several directions seem to be undeveloped, particularly related to some of the skills people have. There were some very interesting possibilities sugggested and an obvious ending or two absent.Still a few bugs in the quests, especially when you do them out of order.Even at the highest level, infection is too rare. Having more infections, but with the possibility of cures or longer term suppression would have balanced it better.You must take your own character on missions. This makes a combat build important early on.A great pity that an unfortunate early release and negative feedback seems to have killed future games."
