76561197979920540,Recommended,239840,33241654,Posted: 4 July,all,Adric,"I first started playing Dead State when it was in Early Access, and perhaps 70% finished.  I had a lot of fun with it, but it was also not possible to complete and eventually hit a wall where I had to wait it out for the full release.  After a long while, the full game being released + the Reanimated update, I went back and completed it and would recommend the game strongly to those who enjoy old-school, turn-based starategy as well as post-apocalyptic, zombie-filled settings.Pros:- Strong writing for the most part, with a very diverse set of characters and situations that can arise.- An appropriate sense of dread, especially in the early-going.  In the first few in-game weeks, you will likely be short on just about everything, and each day's work to scavenge more supplies will be of great importance.  Depending on which allies you find first, you may find yourself in some fairly precarious situations.- The ruined Texas setting feels alive - or maybe, undead.  In addition to zombies and enemy humans, there are also survivors who are non-hostile, but who also won't join you.  It's a small detail, but it helps to flesh out the landscape and population of the game.- The game has a nice sense of humor to it, despite the bleak setting.  Numerous store and business names parody well-known ones from the real world - the gas station chain T-Rexaco is probably my favorite, but there are a number of good ones.- The morale system is also nice - you can only ever reduce people's unhappiness to acceptable levels.  There's no such thing as a truly happy person in the middle of the end of the world.- The combat is quite excellent, and ramps up in difficulty appropriately as you progress, and you can accomplish some nice strategies (such as foisting zombies on enemy thugs and cleaning up what's left afterwards).- Very diverse and interesting set of characters, with a variety of crisis situations and backstories to work through.Cons- The game is 25% too long, and there's just no other way to put it.  Eventually you will reach a point where you are relatively well off in terms of food and supplies, and now you're just grinding out the days to stay stocked until the endgame hits (which happens a certain number of days in).- Once you've accomplished whatever backstory or crisis issue rests with a character, you will, for the most part, have no real reason for interacting with them anymore, unless it's to boost their morale.- It may seem like a nitpick, but professionally-released games shouldn't have typos.- Although there are some nice features to the interface (automatically stocking key supplies when you return from a scavenging run, instead of having to manually put every food item in storage), they still remain clunky and not all of the perks are properly-balanced.Overall, a very good game, and definitely worth picking up and playing.  To my mind the only real detriment is the extra grind in the back quarter of the game, but if you can push through that, there's no real reason not to get Dead State."
76561197998253663,Recommended,239840,14958430,"Posted: 19 March, 2015",all,Orguss,fun  game got over 100 hours into this i say buy it just wish there was some dlc to continue the game play kinda sad it was over i suggest following the npc story lines add tons to the game just dont play it click and go pay attention to the archs
76561197965049057,Recommended,239840,18999073,"Posted: 10 November, 2015",all,DrunkenHyena,"- Some really interesting bits of writing- Too many NPCs bug you about nonsensical things (""Stop taking me out into the field!"" when I'd never actually done that)- Combat has few tactical options. You can't take cover or delay your action.- Too often you are forced into ridiculous fights (15 zombie on a narrow road with the only exit on the opposite side)- During a fight, the active character cycles between EVERY character on the entire map. Even if they're not active or near you. In some maps, after your guys take a turn, it can take almost a minute of just watching it cycle through zombies that aren't active and do nothing.- The turn order is useless for know when a specific enemy will move since their portrait is only loosely related to their in-world model- There's an option to show which containers on the map can be looted (most can't). This is off by default, and turns itself off each time you play- There are horrible glitches in how it renders area with multiple levels. When on a map like that you will often see people floating in air, or have the ground below you disappear- You can tilt the camera, but only very slightly which makes it hard to see certain areas that you want to move to- You can get ""Status effects"" like poisoned, bleeding, etc. These are shown by an icon, but there is no tooltip when you hover over them so you have to look them up in the manual.- The pathfinding is bad. It will show that you can't reach an area, but if you click a few squares at a time, you'll get there- If you want to move to a square that contains a corpse, you need to carefully target around the corpse.- Having the Science skill means your melee attacks inflict Poison. What?- When looting it shows you how much you are carrying, but not how much you can carry.- The game maintains a To Do list, but even when you complete them they will often not be crossed off- In combat, facing is important but you have no way to change your facing- Weapons have special attacks, but there's no way in-game to see what they are. You have to go read the manual.Overall, it's unpolished and unfinished. If you can get it on sale, it's still worth picking up and trying. I wouldn't pay full price or recommend spending the time to finish the game once it starts to drag."
76561198054149318,Recommended,239840,19942241,"Posted: 25 December, 2015",all,benignlama,"As a diehard Fallout 1,2 and Tactics and State of Decay fan I was immediately pulled into this game. It took a little getting used to, but once you pick it up it is immense fun. I know previous releases have been buggy and there was some negative comment removal issues, but I was fortunate enough to pick up the Reanimated edition so I've only experienced one bug so far on 4 different playthroughs.The gameplay is slow. It's not a zombie slasher/shooter although there certaintly is plenty of turn-based head crushing. This is a game for those who want to manage a group of survivors through the zombie apocolypse ala Rick Grimes style. The characters are well written, the conflicts are dramatic and well thought out. You get attached to some characters while others you may have to leave behind and others you'll wish you had. A must have for dark, mature themed tactical fans and open minded zombie genre nuts."
