76561198032065527,Recommended,239840,12502912,"Posted: 15 October, 2014",all,artka,"I remember reading about this game months ago, and then kind of forgetting about it. After completing a game of Wasteland 2, the turn based RPG bug bit me again.. totally reminding me of FO,FO2, and Jagged Alliance of days past. I searched steam for some more, and rememberd Dead State.Ive put some decent hours into Beta Patch #2 so far and I really like where this is going. Its got all the elements of past turn based RPG's (ie. combat, micromanaging, strategy, building) and more. You wake up as part of a group in a school, which becomes your ""base"". You have to stock that base with food, weapons, etc.. from surrounding areas, all while looking out for zombies and bad guys. Along the way, more can join your group and you have access to all the group for job tasks or scavenging.You dont level up by killing anything, you level up by completing ""shelter goals"". Some of the goals include gathering so much food, med supplies, luxuries, etc.. I thought this was a neat way to gain more skills for your characters, totally away from the norm of killing for skill. I like it.Im on day 25 or so on beta patch #2, and I'm coming to the point where I may have taken in too many people at once, so each day ends up being a search for food more than anything, luckily there are ""fishing spots"" to walk to and test your luck harvesting fish. In fact, I see the potential to have hundreds, if not thousands of locations on the map along with encounters because of the way the map scren and travel works.. this could be a pretty content loaded game moving forward.My Jagged Alliance heart wants to see more specialized firearm variants, as right now, they seem to have one firearm per ammo type. This may be wishful thinking, but would be pretty cool moving forward. I know its the zombie apocalypse, but cant that dead soldier just be carrying a MK17 SD variant or something ;)I'm sure others will complain about the ""graphics"" in some cases, but for me, they dont matter as much.. these games are about the adventure, the open world, the choose your own tasks, the story.. you make it what you want to survive. The true turn based RPG thrives non-linearly, and this game certainly has that potential.All in all, the game is well worth the purchase, even at this early access stage. I think we are in the middle of a turn based RPG game renaissance, and I couldnt be happier about it.  If you like this sort of game, micro managing little pixel squads of people, and, well, the zombie apocalypse.. get Dead State now, you wont regret it."
76561198030752296,Recommended,239840,10171794,"Posted: 19 May, 2014",all,Karasukafka,"The First Seven Days of Dead State's Zombie Apocalypse Tactical Survival GameThe game as it is just a glimse into the final product, call it as an early access, demo or whatever, it is just the first seven days of the storyline with limited access to some of the features. Still, I am very impressed and excited by the game.First of all it is a very traditional old school roleplaying game, the combat is great turn-based, very similar to Jagged Alliance 1 or 2, or Fallout 1 and 2, even to UFO series (the old ones especially). There is character sheets and stats to improve which have some effect in game. Obviously in the end game we might see better how these skills and attributes (and even perks that is not yet in the game but planned) will influence the game and give a boost to replay value.The theme is from the Romero's zombie movies mostly. Zombies are slow, dead bodies, no mutations and freak abilities, differs mostly by the state of corpse. If you are fan of Romero's movies you would like this. If you are expecting a huge range of monsters then you will be disappointed. But if you can get along with it you might have a nice experience. The true enemy is the conditions, the lack of resources, other human beigns who compete for what left, ad your own group. There is a good amount of social dynamism even in such early state of the game and this will be just better. You influence your group morals by what kind of job you assign to them, who are you taking out to the dangerous scavenging missions, how much you listen to their advices and who do you listen to, and so on. There is a hint that there will be some power struggle among the group in later in game.The tactical combat is good enough, if you learn the tricks it is not very hard, but honestly sometimes it can be difficult if you are not careful and the game can punish you very much if you are not careful or do a mistake. That is good in fact and makes the game just more interesting. If you are fan of turn based tactical combat, this game is for you. Weapons do have some special attributes, like cutting weapons can cause bleeding to living beigns, crushing weapons can cause disorientation, with some weapons you can knock your enemy prone and so on. Also there are some psychological conditions in effect, like panic when you are overrunned by zombies (a sure way to die quick).There is penty of improvement to be made of course, and I list some which I think would make the game even in early access better.1) Inventory screen: at this point I could not be able to reach the other survivors inventory at the base, and as you only able to command your main character in the area you have only a very ineffective way to equip your companions. A screen where your in-party companions could be equipped from the base storage would be great). Also it would be nice to be able to drop items to ground or just simply to exchange with others in the tactical maps. At the moment I only found one solution to trade items with companions, and that is to utilize the 'containers' already placed in game, put the items there and then change the control to other character and get those.2) It would be nice to see some notes or hints in the maps you have. You encounter empty houses, or places with some corpses and you wonder what's happened there. It would add to the horror if either you might able to collect clues what happened or youhave your companions comment on the situation.And finally I want to praise the music. It is great, melancholic, sad, but also in a way calming. It gives back something of the theme wandering in a city emptied of life. Well done and thanks fr th experience. I am looking forward to the final game and any updates."
,Recommended,239840,29042135,Posted: 5 January,all,<(ASR)>Dauthi,Beautifully done. Great story. Love the random encounter generator for both occurances and visitable areas. Combat is in depth and the fact that you can become infected adds anouther level of danger when dealing with undead.
76561197971410223,Recommended,239840,13903042,"Posted: 8 January, 2015",all,Falcone,"My thoughts on Dead State my first 2 trys at 20 hours each.Well... fighting zombies, gangs, thugs, and bringing truck loads of loot to disgruntled NPC's only to end up being shot by a dude in a wheelchair I thought was my friend which prompty ended the game...both times.However,My 3rd playthrough is actually going smoother thanks to a few console commands to help with morale issues. (Even if an ally is in a good mood there's a negative penalty to morale. ???) Also I had to use a command to remove some negative permanent status effects not being removed on its own. (I had 3 characters that were on fire for 24 hours)It's a pretty addictive game for the most part. It reminds me of the old-school icewind dale games to some degree. The AI could use some work, a cover system would be a nice touch during gun fights, but over all I found myself frustrated at the bugs in this game but kept playing away anyway."
76561198096126632,Recommended,239840,25265893,"Posted: 31 August, 2016",all,Cazac,Great game after all the updates and fixes. Highly recommended for turn-based strategy geeks.
76561198114272381,Recommended,239840,33764576,Posted: 24 July,all,steelmidnight,"This game surprised me. Its far better then most Tactical games out there in this price range. I personally prefer a fantasy setting over sci fi or horror, but this one is an exception. Its actually ""feels"" apocolyptic, and while most of the gameplay outside of the typical turned based combat is typical loot and scoot,its still done well, and is addictive and fun.There is a tension in the air as well, as you have a ""sound meter"" that if you make to much noise, you will attract some unwanted attention in the form of Zombies by the hordes. This meter is even still active DURING battle, so firing off that gun to save your♥♥♥♥♥may actually get said♥♥♥♥♥eaten. Zombies can also tackle a member of your gang of mismatched heros to the ground if they outswarm them, even at full health, leading to an instant kill if you dont hurry and help get the zombies off them. Bites can also infect a person, killing them and turning them into a zombie if you dont give them daily anti biotics. And while it  is not easy to get infected by a bite (unless your being careless or overzealous) it adds to the tension even more.Zombies are not the only threat. You also need to deal with marauders, bad cops, biker gangs, looters, and raiders, and even other paranoid or desperate survivors who want your resources.Your ""base"" is an old school, which you can populate with a WIDE variety of characters. These characters are not cut and paste, as they all have thier uses such as mechanics or soldiers, to meth addicts and doctors. No too are alike, and they dont always play nice with you or each other. But if you handle the situations well, you can keep them all useful and under control. Handle things the wrong way, and one of your characters may be murdered in thier sleep by another, or you may wake up to find one of them stole your resources and ran off in the middle of the night. Its VERY nice to see this much depth in a game I had low expectation for going into.This hybrid Turn based strategy/tactical game/Zombie apocalypse simulater/social simulator/exploration and plundering game is a MUST for Turn based rpg/strategy gamers and zombie apocalypse fans in general! Would LOVE to see a fantasy game using this same system! Two thumbs WAY up!"
