76561197980259241,Recommended,239840,34089957,Posted: 7 August,all,Voen,"I'm going to give this game a thumbs up, but there are quite a few caveats to go along with it. Its one of those many situations where a 'mixed' review would be what I'd rather pick, but forced to choose I think I land on the thumbs up side.Tl;dr: The storyline, characters, immersion and world-building are awesome, in my opinion. The capacity to make choices as you go within the world is a big factor in this. There is a ton of content, as I put in over a hundred hours and hadn't even beaten it for the first time yet (just got tapped out on the systems themselves). The RPG elements of it are really unique and enjoyable as well. However, the game is not polished, combat is awkward at best and outright broken at worst, and ends up feeling very tedious. To beat the harder enemies, your best bet is often to use 'cheesy' strategies to make up for how awkward the system is itself. Overall, I really enjoyed it, but its ~70 rating on metacritic makes sense in light of the lack of polish.First, it is not polished. There is a reason this game has a ~70 on metacritic. It is very sloppy in a lot of ways, and lots of things do not work well. Despite looking like it is from 2005, it still runs very poorly at moments when the environments get at all 'complex' or over-populated.Second, the combat is quirky at the best of times, awkward or broken at the worst. This is kind of a tie in to the first point on the game being polished, but it deserves its own note. I ended up not beating the game just because the process of fighting the undead, and even humans, became tedious after awhile. It was often necessary to use 'cheesy' strategies, such as screwing up the human enemies on doors (which they could not deal with effectively / intelligently most of the time) For context, I've beaten X-Com 1 from start to finish twice, and I've beaten Divinity: Original Sin. I don't normally tire easily of strategic combat games, but this one took it out of me to the point that, after over 100 hours played, I am throwing in the towel and calling the enjoyment I had of the game to where I reached a victory of its own.Third, it is not pretty. The character pictures are well done, but the actual models in the game are, as mentioned above, reminiscent of games from a decade older than Dead State. That has never really mattered to me all that much in games, but even I got a little bored with its lacklustre visuals.So, now that that is out of the way, why am I giving a thumbs up? Well, first off, I clocked over a hundred hours and *didn't beat it yet.* So as far as bang-for-your buck between play time and cost goes, this game is pretty damn economic. And to be clear, I did enjoy the first 100 hours. It was only once I continued to slide past that point, and discovered through looking online that I still had a loottt more to do, that I threw in the towel.Nextly, and this is the main thing for me, the writing, categories and world-building are phenomenol. Despite looking quite bluch, the game has really excellent writing and a huge cast of characters who are unique in their own way. They do a really excellent job as well of having the characters personalities reflected in their stats and decision-making. Many characters will have unique events and relationships that emerge between one another, even if they didn't know each other outside of the shelter. And the decision-making is far more reminsicent of Fallout 1 or 2 than more recent games that claim to give you a lot of choice. One of the advantages of forgoing voice acting is they can pile on the dialogue and character choice options without as much concern.So that's dead state in a nutshell. I'm done with it for now, but I think I may come back in a few years and use a walkthrough to try and find / save all the characters that you can (if that's even possible). Last thing I should probably note is this is a pretty cut and dried zombie survival game in a lot of basic ways, so if that's your jam you'll probably like it, but if that's a big turn off, you might find the cons I mentioned even more overpowering, and the pros inadequate."
76561198287475338,Recommended,239840,33993345,Posted: 3 August,all,bunny de fluff,"Dead State Reanimated is a 3D zombie wrecking turn-based RPG that reminds me of Fallout 2(the combat not the story). There is  some base building, scavenging and item crafting, and a lot of fight. You could find a lot of 3-way war in this game, with you fighting both zombies and human enemies, or you could stand aside and watch them fight it out if you'd mastered the art of zombie luring. If the human enemies were killed by zombies, they come back to life as zombies too. There are a lot of weapons and armors to choose from. Objects in the maps are quite detailed. And the most brilliant thing about this game is all the recruitable survivors with their own stories and their own interactions and dialogues between them. Took me around 120 hours to complete it. Very recommended."
