76561198032079587,Recommended,239840,13134389,"Posted: 28 November, 2014",all,Civplayer,"I am not a big fan of RTS games (I'm old and slow) so I tend to really gravitate towards turn based games.  So naturally I was very interested in Dead State and followed its development for some time (seems like a really long time).  I didn't actually buy it and begin playing until update 3. I really wanted to wait until release but curiosity got the best of me.There aren't a whole lot of games that do turn based isometric combat really well.  Dead State doesn't do anything new in that regard either, in fact the combat, even though it can be quite a challenge until you get decent armor, weapons and skills it is really very simple. There is no cover, crouch, stealth or very many combat options at all. But it still manages to be very engaging and fun.  With that said it really isn’t the combat that make this game so engrossing.Dead State does a great job of drawing you into the world it’s created.  You need to struggle to survive. You need to struggle to keep your base running. You need to struggle to get along with your ever growing group of personalities, oops I meant fellow survivors.  You’re in charge but you’re challenged to stay in charge.  You have to choose whether to allow in, or to keep some useful troublemakers.  Word of warning some people might not be what they seem to be!As the game has developed through various updates; it’s now on update 5.5, the dialog has gotten a little more polish. It is fairly deep as it is but it could be deeper, just a slight knock in that department. The stories are compelling but a little shallow. There is plenty to do at the base, but also not much to do at the base at the same time. I know that’s confusing let me explain.The game progresses at the close of each day, sort of a big ""end of turn"".  Every day you set up your job assignments and go out into the word to scavenge. Back at base after you talk to your fellow survivors, there a few lines of dialog and dialog choices and that’s pretty much it. So even though you begin to care about some of your survivors and your base there really isn’t any way to satisfyingly interact with your base or fellow survivors.In closing what you have here is a very solid good time playing in a zombie apocalypse.  It isn’t very deep but it is still very satisfying and it will eat up a big chunk of your time as you get into that, ""well let me just see what happens tomorrow"" (or the just one more turn) mindsetOverall I’d rate it a solid 7.5 out of 10, it loses points because its combat is somewhat primitive and the stories inside your home community are a little shallow.This game is well worth the cost and well worth your time if you are at all interested it this genre, in other words, BUY IT! PLAY IT! I doubt you’ll regret it!"
76561198071927590,Recommended,239840,13448685,"Posted: 19 December, 2014",all,Yograin,Very well written game with interesting story and good atmosphere. Do not expect it to be mainly combat focused as the combat is bit trivial.What I find really outstanding are the personnal stories of the cca. 40 survivors you can have in your shelter.As of 19.12.14 the game isn't as polished as it could and should be and some bugs might spoil your experience. Not all endings are implemented and some personnal stories of your survivors are incorrectly sequenced/finetuned but the majority is done properly and there are really many of them.Very nice addition to the game is the possibility to decode messages and files(150 of them) from other survivors where you can read stories how the disaster happened and some other interesting reading. Conspiracy theories etc. fitting well with the overall atmosphere of the game.Building and running your shelter and its inhabitants is done nicely even if it might not be challenging for experienced players.
