,Recommended,239840,13513051,"Posted: 21 December, 2014",all,DevilMedic,"This is my second review for Dead State.  My first review was written almost immediately after release and was highly negative.I started playing the day of release, but it still had quite a few issues back then. I'm on my ""third"" character, but have yet to actually finish the game. I started anew after the recent patch as pretty much all of the ragequit worthy bugs that I had encountered worked themselves out.That being said, I have played many indie titles on steam. This IS A GOOD BUY. My initial opinion was the opposite, but I can't stand by that anymore. The Devs and Mods are a very close knit group and the communication between them as well as the community is amazing. I would not be surprised one bit if they continue adding content over time, which seems pretty common with indie crews that create a game out of PASSION like they did, and not out of a pricepoint.Lot's of peoples main question regarding a SP only game is the replay value and length of the game, I will give you my thoughts on that first.REPLAYAs it stands right now the game is definitely fun for at least one playthrough, and it is a LONG playthrough. There are lots of places to explore and cool things to see, as well as special weapons to hunt down, achievements, special enemies and special recruitable characters as well.  Now I have not reached the end-game.  I have one character around day 55ish right now, another around 45, and my first character is somewhere between 60-70, I believe.  As far as I can tell neither of them are super close to the end of the game.  A lot of it has to do with your playstyle, as well.  I made it a point to maneuver the entire world map on my last character and have found ALL SORTS of stuff I had no idea about, which will elongate my game.  Think Fallout2,  tt could be a 20 hour game, or a 100+ hour game.  While this is not as in depth as Fallout 2, the same principle stands.  IMO, at 30 bucks, even if this game was 30 hours it would be worth it.  A dollar an hour of entertainment?  Ok, deal.This current character is my third to reach roughly day 50 so far.  Even having replayed those fifty days three times now, it was not a complete grind like I thought it would be.  The key to keeping this game interesting for me was varying my character builds.  First character was firearms.  Second, melee.  My current character is a bow character (STR and PER), and is INSANELY fun to play.  Granted, there are those ""Oh, great, I have to do THIS part again"" feelings, but the majority of those were routed in some bugs from older versions AS WELL as my not fully understanding the game mechanics on previous plays.COMBATCombat is... Well, it is honestly not the best.  It doesn't necessarily detract from your first playthrough, but there are no cover mechanics (xcom) and once you get some decent gear the zombie fights are as tense and nerve wracking as beating up sleeping ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ toddlers with a cricket bat.  But, the devs state several times that zeds are supposed to be easy, and it is the human NPC's that are trouble.AIMuch like the original Fallout and Fallout 2, enemies are NOT scaled to your level.  This means if you wander into the wrong spot too early, you are going to have a REAL bad time.  I always enjoyed games that did this, so while I think it's a great perk, some may think it's poor design.Currently, enemies are static unless agro'd by a noise or by seeing you, though I think I saw a dev or mod say they were working on a patrolling AI?  Once again, does not impact your first playthrough much/at all.WEAPONS/ARMORThere is a decent selection of armor available in the game, which all have their pro's and con's and will make the critical gamer think hard.  ""Do I want to sacrifice an AP for more defense, or would I rather give myself an extra chance to hit?""  Helmets with visors and masks will affect that characters visual range, which I thought was a very nice touch.  Higher grade armors CAN be hard to find, there may come a point when you think the entire selection is leather jackets and tactical vests.  Not true!The weapons are equally varied, and also have the added spice of unique named weapons.  These are the money makers.  Increased crits, THC, damage, custom look and names, and they usually come with a little backstory.  VERY fun once you get some of them!You also have the ability to create minor upgrades for some of your firearms and armor through the use of a player built workshop.STORYLINESome of it is event driven, some of it is time driven.  It moves along at a fair pace, not so fast that you don't have time to explore the map, and not so slow that you get bored (generally, there are a couple times where I thought my game was bugged because nothing was advancing, then the next day... it did.)You also learn more about the survivors you recruit.  Nearly every one will come to at some point asking you to perform X task for Y reason.  Some are time sensitive, others are not.  They usually ALL give you a little glimpse into their backstory, however.This game puts almost more stress on the aspect of MANAGING a post apocalyptic shelter than it does fighting zombies.  You will get crisis events and your ""sub-leaders"" (key NPC's in your shelter) will voice their opinions.  I have yet to see one where an answer you give will make EVERYONE happy.  Some of them require you to put a little thought in and weigh risk vs reward, i.e should I spend these supplies to prevent something that MIGHT NOT happen, just to be safe?  Or should they be put to use on a more immediate issue elsewhere?Additionally, certain NPC's react differently to different conversations.  If you have a raging hard♥♥♥♥♥with a meanstreak that lived a rough life, are you going to coddle them and bend to their whim, or draw a hard line to make them respect your role?There is not a lot of written/spoken backstory for the majority of locations, however I have not come across a single map that didn't leave something to the imagination (assuming someone has one :p ).I would recommend my friends buy this game at full price. The fact that it is on sale would make me buy it for them if they were still on the fence.You can go ahead and look at my previous posts, when I first got here I was HIGHLY critical of the game on release. I have done a complete 180. This group of devs got me, and they got me ♥♥♥♥ing good."
76561198020909122,Not Recommended,239840,13840079,"Posted: 4 January, 2015",all,Vosiler,"Combat is sup-par everything else is ok but you have no combat options apart from move, stand still or either of them + attack"
76561197992999760,Recommended,239840,12806002,"Posted: 5 November, 2014",all,Shrapnel,"Game delivers exactly what it promised: Team-based, 3/4 tactical zombie survival / base management in open world environment. There's a lot to sink your teeth into with this one. Basically you lead this bunch of survivors and every morning you get a quick briefing of things / place to explore before setting them to work and you and your scavenging party set out to find some resources to survive another day.Throughout your travels you'll come across other survivors, some good, some not so much. But its you against the zeds so every live body helps. There's lots to explore and different modes of travel, and the shelter will requires lots of upgrades to turn it into a haven amongst all the chaos around you. There are items you need to collect to improve survivor's morale throughout your travels, in turn they will give you advice and mark locations on your map for you to explore. The overland map presents lots of random encounters during your travels, some good, some bad.The shelter is what it's all about. You are constantly struggling with the other survivors to turn this little elementary school into a bonafide ZA haven. And it has all the ability to do it, with 2 floors and multiple rooms you will have everything you and your survivors will need to survive the nights of Splendid if you plan accordingly.Combat starts off appearing simple but as you get more followers and more weapons you can then start to have very tactical battles, with different status effects and AOE biological weapons to help keep the battle in your favor, making impossible-looking battles into 3-round wipe ups if you're careful. Both ranged and melee are viable (I stick to melee, this is a ZA)The maps run from classic overrun parks and hospitals, to dark scenes of lost hope, to some really...unique scenarios that I wouldnt have expected. Games like these are what makes all the risk of joining an EA worthwhile. Would highly recommend."
