76561198042371381,Not Recommended,239840,10467164,"Posted: 13 June, 2014",all,Melony,"I want everyone to know right here and now that DoubleBear has been exhibiting some very inappropriate business practices, in my opinion. This review is to tell the community of those practices, as well as reviewing the game itself.People, you arebasicallybeing lied to by DoubleBear.Before you write a response to my review, please be sure to read my entire review first. I understand if you only want to skim it, and that's fine, but please try not to make an argument until you DO fully read the whole thing. I'd like to not repeat myself, but I do understand that I will be writing a lot and it's hard to read it all.I want to inform all of you that I will not only be reviewing this game, but also the business practices of the developers, DoubleBear. There is some very inappropriate behavior going on on their end and I want the community to know about it. I'm going to tell everyone about it very calmly, and very fairly, but I'm going to be 100% brutally honest. I want the community to know, because they have a right to, and I will be very appropriate about it so there will be no reason to accuse me of being abusive, rude, or anything of the sort. I want to make that very clear.As a disclaimer: If I edit this review, I willalwaysleave everything I originally wrote in this review. I am the sort of person who will admit their mistakes, (unless it's a typo, I'll fix typos without telling you I did that, I mean come on) and who doesn't like to change what was originally there. I will always tell you whatever I am editing (again, unless it's a typo), so that way the integrity of this, and myself, is never compromised.First of all, I want to say that this is a pretty good game. I don't prefer turn-based games, but for a turn-based game, it's not bad at all. A little bit basic, there doesn't feel like there's much meat to it, and maybe that's just because I'm so used to my games having voice acting in them or something, I'm not sure. It's true that it's only essentially a Beta version of a demo, so of course it's not that developed - and I understand that, that makes sense.But that is all you are currently purchasing. A demo. This is not an Early-Access game. It is the first 7 days of the game, and you will never get any more days until the full game is released.That is one of my main problems with this game. You are,essentially,being lied to by the developers. It used to be they had the word ""demo"" plastered everywhere, all over their game summaries and descriptions and even in the early-access disclaimer thing. Now, you can't find the word ""demo"" anywhere, and on top of that, the limit of them informing you what you are actually purchasing for $25 are only these two sentences:""Dead State is currently in Early Access - purchasing now will eventually unlock the full game for you at final release, and in the meantime you can playtest the first seven days of the game (ongoing feature updates are planned).""and""Dead State: The First Seven Days is an early, WIP preview of the first week of Dead State's gameplay - an opportunity to prepare your strategy for the full game and help us test and polish the full Dead State experience.""To the layman? Who only skims the description because, let's be honest, a good majority of people? Only skim. This looks like it is saying ""For now you get the first 7 days, but maybe as we go along until release, we'll be releasing more days."" -- Becausethat is what Early-Access is, or at the very least is supposed to be -- that is what the majority of gamers on the planet AGREE Early-Access means.People, I want to be very clear:When you purchase this game, right now. When you click that green button, go to your cart, and click the green 'purchase for myself' button, you are spending $25 on a 7-day demo of this game. The most that will happen to that demo is small updates to it, like new items, the battle system itself vaguely changing, and maybe some text changing. You will never, ever, ever get past those first 7 days of gameplay. Not until the full game releases. That is a fact. That is a completely indisputable fact.****I have a lot more to add on here, but I can not fit it all on this review page.Please, please, pleaseclick the link to Gamespot at the bottom of this review and read the whole thing, at the very least do so before commenting on my review.****Now, to my actual gameplay review:The game is alright. I know it seems like I couldn't have played enough for very long, but believe me, I got enough time to play that I know exactly what the game is about and how it works.In all honesty? It's kind of like a Zombie Apocalypse version of Pokemon Mystery Dungeon. There are some tweaks here or there, obviously, but generally speaking it's very similar. If you're not careful, you could end up inadvertently shoving a character in the middle of like 8 zombies at once, and though that's a true danger in most zombie apocalypse worlds, I have a hard time believing my other characters would take about 8 turns before saving him. That was literally the first thing that happened to me when I went into the game. I literally quit and started over again because the game gave me absolutely NO warning that something like that could happen.Now, maybe it's just me, and maybe it's just because it's been areallylong time since I played a turn-based game last, but when I played this game, I got absolutely NO instruction on how to play, whatsoever. And again, maybe it's just because I'm a moron -- I definitely can be, from time to time. But when I first played, I had no idea what was better - was the knife better? Or was the bat better? I had no idea, because I had no idea what the difference (in this game) piercing damage was in comparison to blunt damage. I mean of course most people assume piercing damage DOES more damage, but honestly some basic gamers may not know that, and they're not very clear about it.On top of that, I had absolutely no idea that, when I started, the zombies were all gonna get 2 fighting turns in a row and I was only going to get 1. I also didn't know that even if the screen was clear, they could still appear later, around corners and the like - again, I know that SHOULD be generally common sense, but I've been spoiled by all of the other open-world games out there, and I'm used to a goblin being around a corner before I even get around that corner. I've played so many various games that I NEED to be told the rules in a game like this, I can't just predict them, because I've just played so many other games with so many other rules.Also, for the record, the graphics are pretty bleh. Even for an early version of the game. I mean it's 2014, we expect quite a bit more out of games these days, even top-down turn-based ones.EDIT:THIS IS NOT MY FULL REVIEW.This is only PART of my review. Unfortunately, my full Review cannot fit on this page - so, for the moment, this is all I can give you - I've managed to cut this review down quite a bit, and now you can find the very, very basics in THIS review. However, there is a LOT more that needs to be covered, and it IS covered at the website I have listed at the end of my review.But for now, please read this review with a grain of salt, as it needs some editing and it is not my full review.Please go to the below website to read my full review before commenting below. If you comment below after only reading the very little tidbits I've written above, I will know. You are absolutely welcome to post without reading my full review, but know that I won't be able to take you entirely seriously if you do something like that.EDIT: For now, please read my full review here:http://www.gamespot.com/dead-state/forums/dead-state-review-31359805/?wikiTypeId=5000&wikiId=97268"
