76561198009779678,Not Recommended,239840,14813667,"Posted: 9 March, 2015",all,KatArus,"I followed this game through it's development and I'm more disappointed in people who created it than in the game itself. A good writer is just that - a good writer. Albeit even being merely good is not enough to create a complex branching CRPG script. On top of that  you also need a good artist, a few competent programmers and a talented game designer to pull everything together. This game have had none of the above, except a good writer. I doubt it could have passed as 'OK' even in late 90s-early 2000s.After my 4th attempt ended in a similar 'I don't want to go through this anymore' fashion I uninstalled the game and decided to recap my experience with it, perhaps this will save someone couple o' dozen hours of their life.To boot, the only character you can build from scratch is your protagonist and you can influence a handful of others, some for a bit, others a lot. The key word is 'influence'. All NPC characters have predetermined skill and stat progression preset and, once recruited, they will slowly levelup on a daily basis regardless of their state or occupation. E.G. on day 2 NPC will gain +1 medicine skill regardless if he spent all that day murdering zombified and hauling loot, unclogging crappers, being treated in the infirmary or not doing anything at all. WTF? I expected having a mishmash of different people and then shape them accordingly to their tendencies, personality and community's needs over the months that pass ingame. At this early point my immersion crashed so hard that it never recovered.Every other system in the game works exactly the same.1. The county is littered with parked cars whose owners didn't make it to them, you can drain their fuel, loot their luggage, but you have to repair a broken car at your base to be able to drive one.2. I had to make a screenshot of the ingame map and use Paint to write notes on it to track places i've been to and looting progress, so yeah, no tooltips, no tracking, no useful dynamic in-game info so consult PDF manual before every fart if you don't want to shoot yourself in the foot.3. You receive harsh morale and stat penalties if you don't make it back from your looting trip before nightfall because... well... because. Albeit threre is no ingame way to know how long it will take to get anywhere. You just go to the world map, walk in a straight line until your ingame clock shows that you're at a point of no return (count what time of the day it is yourself) and cut out a piece of paper of this length and use it as a ruler on my monitor. Feeling ridiculous yet? There's more4. You didn't make in back in time. Boo-hoo. You are now fatigued for the whole day instead of being able to sleep a couple more hours. Day starts at 8 a.m. Get your♥♥♥♥♥out of the bed. NAOW. Okay, someone else can lead looting squad out, that nosy sheriff, for example, he's basically my lieutenant-in-command now, right? RIGHT? Nope. Uhm... why am I playing this, again?I could keep going like this for hours, since there are no actual pros to counteract all theese shortcomings. I was hungry for a game like this, I eagerly waited and then convulsively barfed every time I tried to take a bite.TL,DR Overall game design is plain HORRENDOUS, from combat to character progression. It's basically a linear zombie apocalypse novel that came to be as a game because of studio founder's 'making a good oldschool RPG can't be that hard' attitude. Has zero saving graces as a game. Wasted money."
